Goal:¶

The goal of this report is to demonstrate expertise in building and training different classes of machine learning models.

The models we will build in this report are:

  1. Univariate polynomial regression models
  2. Multivariate Polynomial models
  3. Decision Trees
  4. kNNs

Ultimately, we will try to predict the risk of diabetes progression in patients using these ML models that are trained on sklearn diabetes dataset.

In this lab we will evaluate the models using R-squared, Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) metrics.

1.0 Introduction¶

1.0.1 About the Dataset¶

The diabetes dataset used in this report is one of sklearn's toy data set. It contains ten baseline variables, age, sex, body mass index, average blood pressure, and six blood serum measurements that were obtained for each of n = 442 diabetes patients, as well as the response of interest, a quantitative measure of disease progression one year after baseline.

Data Set Characteristics:

Number of Attributes: First 10 columns are numeric predictive values

Target: Column 11 is a quantitative measure of disease progression one year after baseline

Attribute Information:

  • age (age in years)
  • sex
  • bmi (body mass index)
  • bp (average blood pressure)
  • s1 tc, (total serum cholesterol)
  • s2 ldl, (low-density lipoproteins)
  • s3 hdl, (high-density lipoproteins)
  • s4 tch, (total cholesterol / HDL)
  • s5 ltg, (possibly log of serum triglycerides level)
  • s6 glu, (blood sugar level)

Note: Each of these 10 feature variables have been mean centered and scaled by the standard deviation times the square root of n_samples (i.e. the sum of squares of each column totals 1).

The Problem:

The aim is to be able to predict the the disease progression of the patient a year after the baseline data is recorded. We want to train the machine learning model to predict the risk of diabetes progression over a year. This would be a tool to help physicians with Identifying patients at risk.

5.0 Modelling, Evaluation and Conclusion (Part 2)¶

5.0.1 Univariate Polynomial Regression¶

First, we'll train a univariate polynomial regression model on the BMI feature versus the "disease progression one year after baseline" - from degree 0 to 5.

i. Train and evaluate 6 models of degree 0-5¶
In [13]:
# Initialize dictionary to store models and their properties for use outside the loop
models = {}

# Loop over the reange of degrees and define polynomial model for each degree
for degree in range(0,6):
    # declare model key in dictionary
    models[f"model_{degree}"] = {}
    if degree == 0:
        polynomial = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    else:
        # No need to introduce noice if degree is not equal to zero
        polynomial = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=False)

    # fit the model to a polynomial olf the degree specified
    X_poly_train = polynomial.fit_transform(X_train)
    feature_names = polynomial.get_feature_names_out()

    # Save feature names and polynomial in dictionary
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["feature_names"] = feature_names
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["polynomial"] = polynomial

    # Initialize the Linear Regression Model
    model = LinearRegression()
    
    # Fit Model using the transformed X train values and y train
    model.fit(X_poly_train, y_train)

    # save the model in the dictionary for use outside the loop
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["model"] = model

    # Use the model to predict the train values, evaluate and store the model metrics
    y_poly_train_pred = model.predict(X_poly_train)

    models[f"model_{degree}"]["r2_score_train"] = metrics.r2_score(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["mae_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["mape_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)   

    # Use the model to predict the validation values, evaluate and store the model metrics 
    # We use polynomial.transform to transform the validation dataset into a form that the model understands
    # because the model was fitted with the transformed X_train values
    y_poly_val_pred = model.predict(polynomial.transform(X_val))

    models[f"model_{degree}"]["r2_score_val"] = metrics.r2_score(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["mae_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)
    models[f"model_{degree}"]["mape_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)

iii. Identify the best model¶

The best model of the 6 models trained above is model 5 (i.e the model with degree 5)

Justification:

  • Model 5 has the highest R-Squared score of 0.354100. For R-Squared score, Higher is better.,Since R-Squared score is the measure of how much variance in the data is explained by the model, this means that model 5 explains the variance in the data more than all other models.
  • Model 5 has the lowest MAE and MAPE. For error metrics like MAE and MAPE, Lower is better., Since our aim is to minimize the residuals between the actual and predicted values, the model with the lower error metric is considered better.

viii. How many trainable parameters are we fitting for each of the models? Explain these values.¶

Trainable Parameters per model

In [20]:
for key in models.keys():
    print(f"{key}: {models[key]["feature_names"]}")

model_0: ['1']
model_1: ['bmi']
model_2: ['bmi' 'bmi^2']
model_3: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3']
model_4: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3' 'bmi^4']
model_5: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3' 'bmi^4' 'bmi^5']

These trainable parameters represent the features used in each of the polynomial regression model trained above.

Understanding the Features in Each Model

  1. model_0: ['1']
    • This means the model only includes an intercept (bias term) with no actual bmi feature. This is the baseline model that predicts the a constant value for all inputs.
    • Equation: $y = w_0$
  2. model_1: ['bmi'] --> Fitting one feature
    • This is a linear model that includes only the bmi feature.
    • Equation: $y = w_0 + w_1bmi$
    • This model assumes a straight-line relationship between bmi and the target variable.
  3. model_2: ['bmi' 'bmi^2'] --> Fitting two features
    • This introduces a quadratic term (bmi^2)
    • Equation: $y = w_0 + w_1bmi + w_2bmi^2$
    • This allows the model to capture curvature in the data.
  4. model_3: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3'] --> Fitting three features
    • This extends the model to cubic regression (third-degree polynomial) by introducing (bmi^3)
    • Equation: $y = w_0 + w_1bmi + w_2bmi^2 + w_3bmi^3$
    • This can model more complex relationships, including one inflection point
  5. model_4: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3' 'bmi^4'] --> Fitting four features
    • This is a fourth-degree polynomial
    • Equation: $y = w_0 + w_1bmi + w_2bmi^2 + w_3bmi^3 + w_4bmi^4$
    • It can fit even more complex curves
  6. model_5: ['bmi' 'bmi^2' 'bmi^3' 'bmi^4' 'bmi^5'] --> Fitting five features
    • This is a fifth-degree polynomial
    • Equation: $y = w_0 + w_1bmi + w_2bmi^2 + w_3bmi^3 + w_4bmi^4 + w_5bmi^5$
    • It provides even more flexibility

ix. Provide a Conclusion section¶

CONCLUSION: UNIVARIATE POLYNOMIAL REGRESSION

Performance Summary: Model_5 performed best of the 6 models trained. Model_5 is a univariate polynomial model with degree of 5. Here are the performance metrics on the testing dataset.

  • R-Squared: 0.27
  • Mean Absolute Error: 51.75
  • Mean Absolute Percentage Error: 0.43 or 43.02%

While this model performed best of the 6 models trained, we cannot say that the model performed well because the performance metrics do not inspire confidence.

R-Squared value of 0.27 means that only about 27% of the variance in the target data is explained by the model. This is very low, because over 70% of the variance is not explained.

Also, A Mean Absolute Percentage Error of about 43% means that almost half of the time, we would be predicting the output variable wrongly.

Since this model is to be used in determining the risk likelihood for patients, which is a critical issue, it would not be wise to deploy a model with such high error margins.

Limitations and Failures:

  • Higher-degree polynomial models tend to lose explainability because of the higher orders that are added in the equation, making them less practical in real-world applications.
  • We notice that as we increased the order, the model performance metrics kept increasing slightly, this might eventually lead to overfitting and the model not being able to generalize to new data

To improve performance, we can consider including other additional features from the original dataset, or changing the ML algorithm used. This will be done in the next sections

In [23]:
# Initialize dictionary to store models and their properties for use outside the loop
poly_models = {}

# Loop over the reange of degrees and define polynomial model for each degree
for degree in [2,3]:
    # declare model key in dictionary
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"] = {}
    
    polynomial = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=False)

    # fit the model to a polynomial of the degree specified
    X_poly_train = polynomial.fit_transform(X_train)
    feature_names = polynomial.get_feature_names_out()

    # Save feature names and polynomial in dictionary
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["feature_names"] = feature_names
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["polynomial"] = polynomial

    # Initialize the Linear Regression Model
    poly_model = LinearRegression()
    
    # Fit Model using the transformed X train values and y train
    poly_model.fit(X_poly_train, y_train)

    # save the model in the dictionary for use outside the loop
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["model"] = poly_model

    # Use the model to predict the train values, evaluate and store the model metrics
    y_poly_train_pred = poly_model.predict(X_poly_train)

    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["r2_score_train"] = metrics.r2_score(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["mae_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["mape_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_poly_train_pred)   

    # Use the model to predict the validation values, evaluate and store the model metrics 
    # We use polynomial.transform to transform the validation dataset into a form that the model understands
    # because the model was fitted with the transformed X_train values
    y_poly_val_pred = poly_model.predict(polynomial.transform(X_val))

    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["r2_score_val"] = metrics.r2_score(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["mae_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)
    poly_models[f"model_{degree}"]["mape_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_poly_val_pred)

b. Decision Tree Models¶

In this section, we will train two decision tree models on the same data and evaluate the performance of the models, then we will compare.

We will train two models varying the max_depth. we will try out max_depth of 3 and 5.

max_depth is a hyperparameter in decision tree models that controls the maximum depth of the tree. It determines how many levels of splitting are allowed from the root node to the deepest leaf node.

i. Train and evaluate the models¶
In [28]:
# Initialize dictionary to store models and their properties for use outside the loop
tree_models = {}

# Loop over the list of max_depth and define decision tree model for each depth
for depth in [2, 3]:
    # declare model key in dictionary
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"] = {}
    
    # Initialize the Decision Tree Regression Model
    tree_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=depth, random_state=42)
    
    # Fit Model using the X train values and y train
    tree_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # save the model in the dictionary for use outside the loop
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["model"] = tree_model

    # Use the model to predict the train values, evaluate and store the model metrics
    y_tree_train_pred = tree_model.predict(X_train)

    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["r2_score_train"] = metrics.r2_score(y_train, y_tree_train_pred)
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["mae_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_tree_train_pred)
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["mape_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_tree_train_pred)   

    # Use the model to predict the validation values, evaluate and store the model metrics 
    y_tree_val_pred = tree_model.predict(X_val)

    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["r2_score_val"] = metrics.r2_score(y_val, y_tree_val_pred)
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["mae_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_tree_val_pred)
    tree_models[f"model_{depth}"]["mape_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_tree_val_pred)

v. How many trainable parameters are we fitting for each of the models?¶

For a Decision Tree Regressor, the number of trainable parameters corresponds to the number of decision nodes and leaf nodes in the tree.

The total number of trainable parameters in a decision tree includes:

  • Number of splits (internal nodes): Each split is based on a feature and a threshold value.
  • Number of leaf nodes: Each leaf contains a predicted value.
In [31]:
for model_num in tree_models.keys():
    number_of_nodes = tree_models[model_num]['model'].tree_.node_count  # Total nodes (splits + leaves)
    number_of_splits = tree_models[model_num]['model'].tree_.n_node_samples.shape[0] - tree_models[model_num]['model'].tree_.n_leaves  # Internal decision nodes
    number_of_leaves = tree_models[model_num]['model'].tree_.n_leaves  # Leaf nodes

    print(f"Trainable Parameters for {model_num}: ")
    print(f"Total Nodes: {number_of_nodes}")
    print(f"Number of Splits (Trainable Parameters): {number_of_splits}")
    print(f"Number of Leaf Nodes: {number_of_leaves} \n\n")

c. K-Nearest-Neighbor (KNN) Models¶

In this section, we will train two KNN models on the same data and evaluate the performance of the models, then we will compare.

We will train two models varying the value of k. we will try out k = 3 and k = 5.

K represents the number of nearest neighbors considered when making a prediction. It is a hyperparameter that controls the model’s complexity and generalization ability.

i. Train and evaluate the models¶
In [32]:
# Initialize dictionary to store models and their properties for use outside the loop
knn_models = {}

# Loop over the list of Ks and define KNN model for each value of K
for k in [3,5]:
    # declare model key in dictionary
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"] = {}
    
    # Initialize the KNN Regression Model
    knn_model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
    
    # Fit Model using the X train values and y train
    knn_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # save the model in the dictionary for use outside the loop
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["model"] = knn_model

    # Use the model to predict the train values, evaluate and store the model metrics
    y_knn_train_pred = knn_model.predict(X_train)

    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["r2_score_train"] = metrics.r2_score(y_train, y_knn_train_pred)
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["mae_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_knn_train_pred)
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["mape_train"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_knn_train_pred)   

    # Use the model to predict the validation values, evaluate and store the model metrics 
    y_knn_val_pred = knn_model.predict(X_val)

    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["r2_score_val"] = metrics.r2_score(y_val, y_knn_val_pred)
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["mae_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_knn_val_pred)
    knn_models[f"model_{k}"]["mape_val"] = metrics.mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_val, y_knn_val_pred)

Model Performance: After training 4 different types of ML models on the dataset, below is the model performance on the testing set in order of best performance:

  • KNN Regressor Model (k=5) --> 1st
  • Multivariate Polynomial Model (degree = 2) --> 2nd
  • Decision Tree Regressor Model (max_depth = 2) --> 3rd
  • Univariate Polynomial Model (degree = 5, X = bmi) --> 4th

Key Observations:

  • Higher degree in multivariate polynomial models could lead to overfitting
  • Higher max_depth in decision tree models could lead to overfitting
  • Lower k value in KNNs could lead to overfitting
  • The higher the degree in Polynomial models, the more complex the model equation becomes and the harder it is to interpret in real life applications
  • A great training set result does not necessarily imply that the model is good. A good model is one that can balance between training set and validation set results. This suggests that it can generalize over unseen data.

  • We might be able to improve on the KNN model if we try changing some other hyper parameters or if we drop some of the features which do not really influence the target variable.
  • The hyper parameter optimization can be done with the help of some algorithmns
  • ML techniques like the use of Lasso Regularization can help with feature selection to select only features with higher impact on the target variable and train the models on these features.
